Table 6 shows the various probabilities of each first-round matchup occurring (the bold values on the diagonal indicate the “stationary” matchups). For example, Q 1 now has a 46.7% probability of playing Q 16 in the first round, compared to the league-pooling system where the corresponding probability was 100%. Another way to view this is to consider that Q 1 and Q 16 will play each other in the first round if they happen to be in the same conference. Thus, one must calculate the probability of such an event occurring. This process can actually be defined statistically by a hypergeometric distribution as follows: 5 PX=x=hx,n,M,N=MxN−Mn−xNn
where:
N = the population size;
M = the number of “successes” in the population;
n = the sample size;
x = the number of “successes” in the sample.
With N = 16, M = 2, n = 8, and x = 2, the corresponding probability is .467, the identical result that was obtained above when each of the combinations was individually listed. Thus, there is a now only a 46.7% probability that Q 1 and Q 16 will be in the same conference, and hence only a 46.7% probability that they will meet in the first-round. In the conference-pooling system, there is even a positive, albeit very small, probability of Q 1 playing a team as good as Q 8 in the first round. This would occur if the best eight teams were all in conference A, and weakest eight teams were all in conference B.
